    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement was a masterclass in strategic nonviolent resistance, and it's unlikely that the movement could have achieved its goals through more confrontational means. The use of boycotts, sit-ins, and marches was a deliberate choice, as it allowed activists to bypass the entrenched power structures and build public support for their cause. The movement's leaders, including Martin Luther King Jr., were well aware of the risks of violence and chose to prioritize nonviolence as a moral imperative. By contrast, more confrontational tactics would have likely led to further polarization and violence, which would have undermined the movement's goals and legitimacy.",
